  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
<p>The melatonin gummy a parent gave their child last night was probably mislabeled. Not because of a rogue manufacturer, not because of a bad batch—but because, in a 2023 study published in JAMA, researchers tested 25 melatonin gummy products sold across the United States and found that 22 of them, 88 percent, contained a different amount of melatonin than the label stated. One contained no melatonin at all—just 31.3 milligrams of undeclared CBD. The actual melatonin content across products ranged from 74 percent to 347 percent of the stated dose. A 2017 Canadian study had found one product at 478 percent of its label, with 26 percent of tested products contaminated with serotonin, a controlled substance. Reading this data hits like a gut punch: how the hell is this legal? The answer is a 31-year-old law that the supplement industry has spent three decades ensuring stays exactly as it is.</p>
</section>
<section id="the-law-that-built-this" class="reveal">
<h2>A Law Designed to Look the Other Way</h2>
<p>The Dietary Supplement Health and Education Act of 1994—DSHEA—is the legal architecture that makes mislabeled melatonin gummies not just possible but predictable. Under DSHEA, dietary supplements are classified as food, not drugs. The consequence of that classification is not subtle: the FDA cannot require a manufacturer to prove a supplement is safe or accurately labeled before it goes on sale. No pre-market review. No approval process. The burden runs in reverse—the agency must prove a product is dangerous before it can act against it.</p>
<p>At the time of DSHEA's passage, roughly 4,000 supplement products were on the market and the industry was worth approximately $4 billion. Today, the Council for Responsible Nutrition—the industry's own trade association—estimates more than 100,000 products are available to American consumers, and the U.S. market exceeds $50 billion annually. The law hasn't been substantively amended since Bill Clinton signed it. The industry it was supposed to govern has grown by a factor of twelve, and the regulatory framework governing it is identical to the one written when a bottle of Centrum cost $8 and the internet didn't exist.</p>
<p>DSHEA did not pass in a vacuum. It passed over the FDA's objections, after an industry-funded lobbying campaign that generated more constituent mail to Congress than the Vietnam War, according to congressional accounts at the time. Supplement manufacturers, facing proposals for stricter pre-market review, mobilized their customer base with warnings that government bureaucrats were trying to make vitamins illegal. The result was a law that placed the legal responsibility for safety entirely on manufacturers themselves—and gave the FDA jurisdiction to act only after consumers had already been harmed.</p>
</section>
<section id="structure-function-claims" class="reveal">
<h2>The Claim That Requires No Proof</h2>
<p>DSHEA created a specific category of marketing language called "structure-function claims": statements describing how a supplement affects the body—"supports memory," "promotes heart health," "helps maintain healthy joints." These are not health claims in the regulatory sense, which would require FDA review. They require only that the manufacturer notify the FDA within 30 days of beginning to sell the product, along with a disclaimer that the claim has not been evaluated by the FDA. That disclaimer appears in tiny type on virtually every supplement bottle in America. Most consumers treat it as boilerplate. Legally, it is a complete confession.</p>
<p>Prevagen is the most expensive lesson in what structure-function claims enable. Quincy Bioscience has sold the product—a supplement derived from a jellyfish protein called apoaequorin—since 2007, marketing it to seniors as a memory-improvement aid "clinically shown" to reduce memory problems associated with aging. Sales exceeded $165 million before the FTC and New York Attorney General jointly filed suit in 2017. At trial, a jury found that Quincy had not substantiated any of its claims with reliable scientific evidence. The FDA itself, in evidence entered at trial, had noted that apoaequorin is likely digested in the stomach before it could reach the brain. In December 2024, a federal judge issued a permanent injunction forbidding Quincy from making any of the challenged memory-improvement claims. Seven years. $165 million. One injunction. No fine.</p>
<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"The regulatory framework for supplements is broken. The manufacturers are not complying with the law, and the FDA is not enforcing the law."<br>— Dr. Pieter Cohen, Cambridge Health Alliance</p></aside>
<p>The Prevagen case is not exceptional. It is illustrative. DSHEA's structure means a manufacturer can make claims for which it has no evidence, collect revenue for years while regulators build a case, and face—at the end of prolonged litigation—an order to stop doing the thing it was already profiting from. The deterrent architecture here is not broken. It was never assembled.</p>
</section>
<section id="what-the-inspectors-find" class="reveal">
<h2>Self-Regulation's Own Evidence</h2>
<p>The industry's standard defense is that self-regulation works: manufacturers follow Good Manufacturing Practices (GMPs), third parties certify products, and bad actors are the exception rather than the rule. The FDA's own inspection data tests this claim directly and does not support it.</p>
<p>In fiscal year 2018, FDA investigators issued formal violation reports to 54 percent of the dietary supplement facilities they inspected. The year before, 58 percent. In FY19, still above 50 percent. The most common violation, year after year, is the same one: manufacturers failing to establish specifications for the identity, purity, strength, and composition of their finished products. Not exotic fraud. The baseline requirement that a company know what is in its own supplement—a standard it has had since 2007 to meet.</p>
<p>The FDA inspects roughly 500 to 600 supplement facilities per year. There are an estimated 10,000-plus manufacturers operating in the United States. At that rate, most facilities will go years, sometimes decades, without a visit. When inspectors do show up, more than half find problems serious enough to document formally. The industry's claim that self-regulation is working cannot survive contact with its own regulator's own numbers.</p>
<div class="data-callout reveal"><p><strong>On third-party certification</strong></p><p>Voluntary certification programs from NSF International, the U.S. Pharmacopeia (USP), and Informed Sport provide meaningful quality signals and are better than nothing. They are not a substitute for mandatory pre-market oversight. Participation is voluntary, partial, and market-driven—concentrated in brands that can afford the process and see commercial advantage in the credential. They cannot be the system's answer to systemic failure.</p></div>
</section>
<section id="the-drug-problem" class="reveal">
<h2>What Isn't on the Label</h2>
<p>Mislabeled melatonin is a quality control problem. A 2020 review in Mayo Clinic Proceedings describes something more serious: dietary supplements—particularly those marketed for weight loss, sexual enhancement, and muscle building—found to contain undisclosed pharmaceutical drugs. Anabolic steroids. Sildenafil. Banned weight-loss compounds. The review, by Dr. Pieter Cohen of Harvard Medical School, found that the FDA had identified hundreds of such adulterated products. Under DSHEA, a consumer buying a "natural" weight-loss supplement has no mechanism, short of independent lab testing, to know whether it contains an unlisted prescription drug. The FDA had no authority to check before it was sold.</p>
<p>The adverse event reporting system for supplements compounds this. Unlike pharmaceutical manufacturers, who must report all serious adverse events to the FDA, supplement companies are required to report only those events they receive directly—and the system relies substantially on voluntary compliance. Research has consistently found it undercounts real-world harm dramatically. When industry cites low adverse event rates as evidence of safety, that is the methodology underlying the claim: a voluntary, passive surveillance system with known structural gaps, in a $50 billion market with no pre-market scrutiny.</p>
</section>
<section id="the-industry-argument" class="reveal">
<h2>The Real Tension</h2>
<p>The supplement industry's defense deserves honest engagement because part of it is correct. Pre-market approval on the pharmaceutical model—full clinical trials before any product can be sold—would be genuinely costly, slow, and would eliminate the majority of the supplement market, most of which has never been tested in controlled trials and likely never would be. That is a real cost. The FDA does, eventually, act on some serious safety signals, though its track record includes delays and failures influenced by industry lobbying and underfunding. And most supplements, most of the time, do not injure people.</p>
<p>But this argument answers a question nobody is asking. Nobody credible is proposing pharmaceutical-level pre-market approval for vitamin C, though some reform advocates argue for tiered scrutiny based on risk, and industry critics point out that even basic vitamins have faced contamination issues unaddressed by current rules. What reform advocates have consistently proposed is mandatory product listing: a requirement that manufacturers register their products with the FDA before selling them, so the agency knows what exists. Currently, the FDA has no comprehensive inventory of supplements on the market. It cannot recall a product it doesn't know is there. This is not a nuanced policy dispute about regulatory philosophy. It is a gap with no serious defense—and the industry has lobbied against closing it for thirty years.</p>
<p>The Council for Responsible Nutrition opposes mandatory listing requirements on the grounds that the current framework already provides adequate tools. The argument might carry more weight if those tools had produced different results over three decades than what the inspection data, the JAMA study, and seven years of Prevagen litigation actually show.</p>
</section>
<section id="the-thirty-year-question" class="reveal">
<h2>The Architecture Holds</h2>
<p>The FDA spokesperson's response to the 2023 JAMA findings was precise and entirely accurate: "under current law, the FDA does not have the authority to approve dietary supplements before they are marketed, and firms have the primary responsibility to make sure their products are not adulterated or misbranded." This is not a dodge. It is the law, stated plainly. The FDA is structurally constrained by a statute written before the industry existed at anything like its current scale.</p>
<p>What the melatonin data shows—alongside the Prevagen litigation, the GMP violation rates, and the pharmaceutical adulterants found in weight-loss supplements—is not a series of isolated failures by bad actors. It is a system functioning as designed. Manufacturers self-certify safety. Structure-function claims require no clinical evidence. The FDA acts after people are hurt. The industry funds the lobbying to ensure this remains true.</p>
<p>Poison control centers received more than a quarter million calls about pediatric melatonin ingestion between 2012 and 2021: 4,097 hospitalizations, 287 intensive care unit admissions, two deaths. Many driven by accidental overdose. Some driven by something more structural—parents giving children a gummy whose actual dose, in 88 percent of tested products, was not the number on the label. Nobody checked. Nobody was required to.</p>
<p>The gap between what consumers assume is true—that someone verified this before it was sold—and what is actually true is not an accident. It is the product of a specific political moment in 1994 that the industry has successfully defended through every subsequent Congress. Changing it would require overpowering an industry that has spent three decades, and considerable money, ensuring it doesn't have to be changed. That is the actual obstacle. Not science, not evidence, not regulatory capacity. The law stays because keeping it is profitable, and changing it is not yet costly enough.</p>
</section>
